// Loops
// Loops are used to repeat a block of code until a specified condition is met.
// The most common types of loops in JavaScript are for, while, and do-while loops.

// For Loop
// The for loop is a control structure that allows you to repeat a block of code a specific number of times.
// The syntax of a for loop is as follows:  
/*
for (initialization; condition; increment) {
    // code to be executed
}
*/
// The for loop consists of three parts:
// 1. Initialization: This is executed once at the beginning of the loop. It is typically used to initialize a counter variable.
// 2. Condition: This is evaluated before each iteration of the loop. If the condition is true, the loop continues; if it is false, the loop ends.
// 3. Increment: This is executed after each iteration of the loop. It is typically used to update the counter variable.    
// Example:

for (let index = 0; index < 10; index++) {
    console.log(index);
}
// In this example, the for loop initializes the variable index to 0, checks if index is less than 10, and increments index by 1 after each iteration.
// The loop will print the numbers from 0 to 9.

// You can also use a for loop to iterate over arrays or other iterable objects:

const fruits = ["apple", "banana", "cherry"];
for (let i = 0; i < fruits.length; i++) {
    console.log(fruits[i]);
}
// This will print each fruit in the fruits array. The loop uses the length property of the array to determine how many times to iterate.

// For loops can also be nested inside each other to create more complex iterations:        
for (let i = 1; i <= 3; i++) {
    for (let j = 1; j <= 2; j++) {
        console.log(`i: ${i}, j: ${j}`);
    }
}
// In this example, the outer loop runs 3 times (i from 1 to 3), and for each iteration of the outer loop, the inner loop runs 2 times (j from 1 to 2).
// The output will show all combinations of i and j values. 

// break and continue statements can be used within loops to control the flow of execution. 
// The break statement exits the loop entirely, while 
// the continue statement skips the current iteration and moves to the next one.


// Example of break:
for (let i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
    if (i === 5) {
        break;
    }
    console.log(`value of i: ${i}`);
}

// In this example, the loop will print the values of i from 0 to 4. When i reaches 5, the break statement is executed, and the loop terminates.

// Example of continue:
for (let i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
    if (i % 2 === 0) {
        console.log(`Skipping even number: ${i}`);
        continue; // Skip even numbers
    }
    console.log(`value of i: ${i}`);
}
// In this example, the loop will print the values of i from 1 to 9, skipping the even numbers.
// output: 
// Skipping even number: 0
// value of i: 1
// Skipping even number: 2
// value of i: 3
// Skipping even number: 4
// value of i: 5
// Skipping even number: 6
// value of i: 7
// Skipping even number: 8
// value of i: 9


// You can also use a for loop to iterate over the properties of an object using the for...in syntax:
const person = {
    name: "Alice",
    age: 30,
    city: "New York"
};
for (let key in person) {
    console.log(`${key}: ${person[key]}`);
}